%I A198893 #22 May 21 2026 01:17:11
%S A198893 1,4,66,7128
%N A198893 Number of strictly increasing Boolean functions of n variables with n outputs.
%H A198893 P. Hyvernat, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1106.3874v3">Some Properties of Inclusions of Multisets and Strictly Increasing Boolean Functions</a>, arXiv preprint arXiv:1106.3874v3 [math.CO], 2011-2012. Also on <a href="https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-00601505v3">HAL</a>, hal-00601505v3.
%e A198893 For n = 2, the a(2) = 4 strictly increasing functions f are defined as:
%e A198893   f(00) = 00,
%e A198893   f(01) = 01 or 10,
%e A198893   f(10) = 01 or 10,
%e A198893   f(11) = 11.
%e A198893 Any of these functions is strictly increasing: if a 0 is replaced by a 1 somewhere in the input, then a 0 gets replaced by a 1 somewhere in the output too.
%e A198893 Interpreting the output string as a number written in binary and concatenating these numbers for all possible inputs, these 4 functions can be written as 0113, 0123, 0213, 0223.
%e A198893 For n = 3, the a(3) = 66 strictly increasing functions written in the same way are:
%e A198893   01131337, 01131357, 01131537, 01131557, 01132337, 01134557, 01151337, 01151357, 01151537, 01151557, 01152337, 01154557, 01231337, 01231537, 01232337, 01232367, 01234567, 01451357, 01451557, 01452367, 01454557, 01454567, 02131337, 02131357, 02132337, 02132637, 02134657, 02231337, 02232337, 02232367, 02232637, 02232667, 02234667, 02261337, 02262337, 02262367, 02262637, 02262667, 02264667, 02461357, 02462367, 02462667, 02464657, 02464667, 04151537, 04151557, 04152637, 04154557, 04154657, 04261537, 04262637, 04262667, 04264567, 04264667, 04451557, 04452667, 04454557, 04454567, 04454657, 04454667, 04461557, 04462667, 04464557, 04464567, 04464657, 04464667.
%Y A198893 Cf. A198894, A014466.
%K A198893 nonn,more
%O A198893 1,2
